DESeq analysis for 16048R

June 12, 2019

This guide follows the Bioconductor RNA-Seq workflow to find differentially expressed genes using DESeq2 version 1.22.2 and the hciR package on Github to simplify the R code.

Load samples and counts

We will clean the default meta-data sheet and write it to file.

raw_samples <- readr::read_tsv('16048R_2019-06-11.txt')
#  Parsed with column specification:
#  cols(
#    .default = col_character(),
#    `Multiplex #` = col_double(),
#    `Sample Name` = col_double(),
#    `Conc. (ng/ul)` = col_double(),
#    `Vol. (uL)` = col_double(),
#    `Dentinger ssDNA` = col_logical(),
#    `QC Conc. (ng/uL)` = col_double(),
#    `QC RIN` = col_double(),
#    `Ave Insert Size` = col_logical(),
#    `QC Frag Size (from)` = col_logical(),
#    `QC Frag Size (to)` = col_logical(),
#    `Seq Lib Conc. ng/uL` = col_logical()
#  )
#  See spec(...) for full column specifications.
samples <- dplyr::select(raw_samples, ID, `Sample Name`, `Individual`) %>% 
  dplyr::rename(id= ID, name = `Sample Name`, raw_trt = Individual) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(trt = gsub(x = raw_trt,
                           pattern = "Tg +HCC", 
                           replacement = "Tg.HCC",
                           fixed = T)) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(trt = gsub(x = trt,
                           pattern = "Tg+HCC", 
                           replacement = "Tg.HCC",
                           fixed = T)) %>%  
  dplyr::mutate(trt = gsub(x = trt,
                           pattern = "Tg+HCC", 
                           replacement = "Tg.HCC",
                           fixed = T)) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(trt = gsub(x = trt,
                           pattern = "Tg without HCC", 
                           replacement = "Tg.noHCC",
                           fixed = T)) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(trt = gsub(x = trt,
                           pattern = "Non-Tg", 
                           replacement = "noTg.noHCC",
                           fixed = T)) 
samples

readr::write_csv(x = samples %>% dplyr::select(id, name, trt), 
                 path = 'samples.csv')

Remove 6862 features with zero counts and 5803 features with 5 or fewer reads in any sample to create a final count matrix with 20679 rows.

counts <- filter_counts(counts, n = 5)
#  Removed 6862 features with 0 reads
#  Removed 5803 features with <=5 maximum reads

Run DESeq

Run DESeq using ~ trt in the design formula and get the regularized log transforms (rlog) for sample visualizations.

dds <- deseq_from_tibble(counts, samples, design = ~ trt )
#  estimating size factors
#  estimating dispersions
#  gene-wise dispersion estimates
#  mean-dispersion relationship
#  final dispersion estimates
#  fitting model and testing
rld <- r_log(dds)

Plot the first two principal components (PCs) using the rlog values from the top 500 variable genes. Sample 16048X4 is rather distant from all samples as well as its own treatment group ‘noTg.noHCC’. Also sample 16048X8 has a sufficiently different expresion from the ‘Tg.HCC’ group. Whether it makes sense to drop either of these samples from the DESeq2 model is not clear at this point. On a related point, the distribution of samples within treatment groups across the PC1 and PC2 does not appear to strongly support similar levels biological variance across groups. With this few of samples per group it can be hard to determine from the data whether this assumption is true or not. Therefore, we choose to fit 3 separate models involving each of the pairwise groups separately. This decision is supported by the DESeq2 users’ guide.

plot_pca(rld, "trt", width=700)

Cluster all the rlog values using the R function dist to calculate the Euclidean distance between samples.

plot_dist(rld, "trt", na="white", annotation_names_col=FALSE)

Tg.HCC vs. Tg.noHCC

Subset the levels Tg.HCC and Tg.noHCC. Re-filter low-expressing genes.

groups1 <- c("Tg.HCC", "Tg.noHCC")
samples1 <- dplyr::filter(samples, trt %in% groups1) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(trt = droplevels(trt)) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(trt = factor(trt, levels = groups1)) 
stopifnot(identical(samples$id, colnames(counts)[2:11]))
counts1 <- counts[,c("geneid",samples1$id)]
counts1 <- filter_counts(counts1, n = 5)
#  Removed 182 features with 0 reads
#  Removed 1019 features with <=5 maximum reads

Re-fit the DESeq2 model.

dds1 <- deseq_from_tibble(counts1, samples1, design = ~ trt )
#  estimating size factors
#  estimating dispersions
#  gene-wise dispersion estimates
#  mean-dispersion relationship
#  final dispersion estimates
#  fitting model and testing
rld1 <- r_log(dds1)

Re-do PCA.

plot_pca(rld1, "trt", width=700)

Cluster samples.

plot_dist(rld1, "trt", na="white", annotation_names_col=FALSE)

Infer the differences between pairwise comparison Tg.HCC vs. Tg.noHCC at FDR 5%.

res1 <- results_all(dds1, zebrafish94)
#  Using adjusted p-value < 0.05
#  Adding shrunken fold changes to log2FoldChange
#  1. Tg.HCC vs. Tg.noHCC: 19 up and 34 down regulated

Plot fold changes and p-values in a volcano plot.

plot_volcano(res1, ggplot=TRUE, pvalue = 3)

Cluster the top 50 significant genes sorted by p-value and scale by rows, so values are the number of standard deviations from the mean rlog.

x1 <- top_counts( res1, rld1, top=50)
plot_genes(x1, "trt", scale="row", show_rownames=TRUE, annotation_names_col=FALSE)

Save the DESeq results to a single Excel file and R objects to a binary data file to load into a new session. The Excel file will contain raw counts, rlog values, normalized counts, samples and gene annotations in the Excel file.

write_deseq(res1, dds1, rld1, zebrafish94, file = 'Tables/TgHCC_vs_TgnoHCC.xlsx')
#  Tg.HCC vs. Tg.noHCC
#  Saving 7 worksheets to Tables/TgHCC_vs_TgnoHCC.xlsx
#  Note: zip::zip() is deprecated, please use zip::zipr() instead
save(res1, dds1, rld1, zebrafish94, file="Cache/TgHCC_vs_TgnoHCC.rda")
